{"title_page": "Rowallan Division", "text_new": "'''Rowallan Division''' was a [[Royal Navy]] training course based at [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|HMS Raleigh]] between 1980 and 1981. It assisted the [[Royal Navy]] in\u00a0grooming failed candidates from the [[Admiralty Interview Board]] who lacked the appropriate leadership qualities and personal robustness to qualify for [[Midshipman]] training at [[Britannia Royal Naval College|BRNC Dartmouth]]. A rather severe 12-week character building and development course was used to attempt to rectify this lack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.navynews.co.uk/events/event/3695|title=Navy News - Reporting from the Fleet|last=|first=|date=|website=www.navynews.co.uk|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n[[Thomas Corbett, 2nd Baron Rowallan|Lord Rowallan]]\u00a0 was a member of the rich Polson Family who had strong links with the [[Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell|Baden Powell]] Family. They resided just south of [[Glasgow]] at Rowallan.\n\nHis grandfather's and father's interest in the great outdoors generated an interest in [[Outward Bound|outward bound]] activities. Before the war, he was involved in [[Scouting]] and the setting up of a Juvenile delinquent/criminal rehabilitation centre based on outbound activities.\n\nHe served during the [[First World War]] and despite a leg injury, contrived to serve in WW2. He established and was part of a company which formed part of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary force]], evacuated from [[Dunkirk]] in May\u2013June 1940. It was realised soon after that in order to win the war Britain needed a larger quantity of capable officers, as the failure rate on officer selection was high around 65%, and a large invasion force was going to be required.\n\n[[Thomas Corbett, 2nd Baron Rowallan|Lord Rowallan]] was charged with setting something up based on the success of his rehabilitation courses. This resulted in the establishment of the [[Highland Fieldcraft Training Centre]] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20181104170018/http://www.hftca.org.uk/ HFTC]), at Feshie Bridge, [[Cairngorms]], in the [[Highlands and Islands|Highland and Island]] area of [[Scotland]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Rowallan : the autobiography of Lord Rowallan.|last=1895-|first=Rowallan, Thomas Godfrey Polson Corbett, Baron|date=1976|publisher=P. Harris|isbn=0904505111|location=Edinburgh|oclc=3650193}}</ref>\n\nPost war in 1977 the [[British Army|Army's]] [[Regular Commissions Board]] was again suffering a high failure rate (70%+) at Officer Selection and Training, and during research rediscovered the HFTC success and established a Rowallan Company at [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|RMA Sandhurst]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sandhurst : a tradition of leadership|others=Kent-Payne, Vaughan, 1958-, Pugsley, Christopher,, Holdsworth, Angela|isbn=9781781258231|edition= Second|location=London|oclc=1063725066|date = 2017-08-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1970s the [[Royal Navy]]\u00a0 and the [[Royal Marines]] found themselves in a similar but slightly different position to the [[British Army|Army]]. While applications for commissioned entry were reasonably stable many of the young men who appeared before the [[Admiralty Interview Board]]\u00a0 were judged to lack either the self confidence or the maturity to undergo training immediately after [[Admiralty Interview Board|AIB]] at either the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Britannia Royal Navy College, Dartmouth]] or at the [[Commando Training Centre Royal Marines|Commando Training Centre Royal Marines, Lympstone]]\n\nThe [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|RMA Sandhurst]] Rowallan course was adapted as a model for the [[Royal Navy|RN]]/[[Royal Marines|RM]]\u2019s Rowallan Division at [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|HMS Raleigh]] and was refined and shaped to better meet the needs of the service and, for every individual who was selected for this intensive course of leadership training, confidence and team building. Only two [[Royal Marines]] cadets ever undertook Rowallan Division and so the course syllabus was primarily focused on preparing young Cadets for entry to [[Britannia Royal Naval College|BRNC, Dartmouth]]. The [[Commandant General Royal Marines]] accepted the [[Navy Board (1964-present)|Navy Board\u2019s]] invitation to establish and lead the [[Royal Navy|RN]]\u2019s Rowallan Division\u00a0 and committed over 50% of the staff to command and run this course of training given the [[Royal Marines|RM]]\u2019s particular expertise and experience in command and leadership training.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Special Trust and Confidence The Making of an Officer|last=Cathy.|first=Downes|date=2013|publisher=Taylor and Francis|isbn=9780714633541|location=London|oclc=928016989}}</ref>\n\n== Directing staff ==\n'''Senior Staff List:'''\n\n* Major Rick Wiliams [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] WKhM [[Royal Marines|RM]] - ''Officer Commanding''\n* Lieutenant Commander [[John Lippiett]] [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] [[Royal Navy|RN]] - ''Training Officer''\n* Warrant Officer Class 2 David Langley [[Royal Marines|RM]] - ''Divisional Sergeant Major''\n* Chief Petty Officer David Attenborough - ''Stores & Support''\n* Petty Officer (PT) Michael \"Nick\" Carter - ''Instructor''\n* Sergeant Colin Grice - ''Instructor''\n* Sergeant Paul Pitcher - ''Instructor''\n\nOther members of staff included two [[Royal Marines]] who's duties included driving and who delivered overwatch safety protocols when activities were conducted in the field, \u00a0a [[Royal Navy]] [[chef]] to cook for staff in the field and a [[Women's Royal Naval Service|WRNS]] Leading Writer who assisted the Division's [[Sergeant major|Sergeant Major]] \u00a0with administration. An Instructor Officer was attached to the Division on an occasional basis to assist in the supervision of academic studies.\n\nThe emblem of Rowallan Division was the head of a [[Deer|highland stag]].\n\n== Course structure ==\nStudents on the course were given the nominal [[Military rank|rank]] of Cadet and were paid the equivalent of a new entry junior sailor.\n\nThe course schedule was not given to Cadets who were effectively at 30 minutes notice to move at all times. Generally the Division spent alternating weeks either in the field or in [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|HMS Raleigh]].\n\nWhen at [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|Raleigh]] there were generally 2 or 3 sessions of [[Physical education|Physical Training]] per day along with Practical Leadership Tasks. Emphasis during training was also given to improving Cadets\u2019 written and verbal communication skills with the purpose of improving their self confidence when addressing or briefing others. When it was necessary, individual/one on one Lecturing skills training was carried out that proved to be highly successful. Training activities in the field were conducted such as [[Map|map reading]], [[navigation]], [[first aid]], basic [[Radiotelephony procedure|RT]] procedures and [[survival skills]]. The [[Physical education|Physical Training]] included gymnasium work, [[obstacle course]]s and speed marches (often with loaded [[Backpack|Bergens]]) to improve Cadets\u2019 levels of physical fitness. \u2018Log runs\u2019 were conducted where teams of Cadets raced each other while each team carried a [[Utility pole|telegraph pole]] sized log - these were frequent events that all formed part of Rowallan's [[team building]] ethos.\n\nThe Division conducted many exercises in the field and used [[Dartmoor]], [[Bodmin Moor]], [[Snowdonia]] and the [[Brecon Beacons]] (including the [[Pen y Fan]] horseshoe). These exercises progressed thRough increasing levels of physical and mental duress while requiring Cadets to be individually selected at random intervals to plan, manage and organise a particular task that required innovation, imagination, demonstration of a command ability and good communication skills with the team. Cadets became very adept to \u2018expect the unexpected\u2019 that, with the background of their leadership training, assisted them in being able to think and act decisively when under duress.\u00a0 Where environmental conditions required it as a matter of safety, cadets were issued with the then in service [[Clansman (military radio)|Clansman]] combat net radio system. In early exercises Cadets slept in tents and ate standard 24-hour [[Field ration|ration packs]]. In later exercises cadets had to make [[Bivouac shelter|improvised shelters]] and were supplied with live rations in the form of hens and rabbits which had to be killed humanely under instruction and prepared by hand. Frequently crash moves of camps where trainees were ordered to immediately relocate would be initiated by the directing staff usually in the dark of night.\n\nTowards the end of the course, greater emphasis was given to the preparation and delivery of more classroom orientated activities such as short briefs, [[Lecture|lecturing]] and improving written communication skills and attending informal lectures from external speakers who had a record of excellence of [[leadership]] or personal achievement in their own areas of personal endeavour.\n\n== List of courses ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Course Number\n!Cadets Commencing\n!Cadets Completing\n!Success Rate\n!Notes\n|-\n|1\n|12\n|10\n|83%\n|<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n|2\n|24\n|14\n|58%\n|\n|-\n|3\n|18\n|16\n|88%\n|<sup>2</sup>\n|}\n'''Notes:'''\n\n<sup>1</sup>  Course uniquely included two Royal Marines Cadets who both successfully completed Rowallan Division and went on to [[Commando Training Centre Royal Marines|CTCRM Lympstone]].\n\n<sup>2</sup>  Course included Cadet Gary Pettitt who went on to attain the rank of [[Captain (Royal Navy)|Captain]] in the Royal Navy and Cadet Pete Williams who became a [[Commander]].\n\n== Course closure ==\nThe course was disbanded in 1981 due to [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|MOD]] cost savings measures but, in the short time that it existed, Rowallan Division had served its purpose well in [[Graduation|graduating]] significantly more young men into [[Britannia Royal Naval College|BRNC]] than would otherwise have been the case\n\nA reunion was held in 2015 in the form of a [[Mess|Mess Dinner]] at [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|HMS Raleigh]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Naval education and training in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "'''Rowallan Division''' was a [[Royal Navy]] training course based at [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|HMS Raleigh]] between 1980 and 1981. It assisted the [[Royal Navy]] in\u00a0 grooming failed candidates from the [[Admiralty Interview Board]] who lacked the appropriate leadership qualities and personal robustness to qualify for [[Midshipman]] training at [[Britannia Royal Naval College|BRNC Dartmouth]]. A rather severe 12 week character building and development course was used to attempt to rectify this lack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.navynews.co.uk/events/event/3695|title=Navy News - Reporting from the Fleet|last=|first=|date=|website=www.navynews.co.uk|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n[[Thomas Corbett, 2nd Baron Rowallan|Lord Rowallan]]\u00a0 was a member of the rich Polson Family who had strong links with the [[Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell|Baden Powell]] Family. They resided just south of [[Glasgow]] at Rowallan.\n\nHis grandfathers and fathers interest in the great outdoors generated an interest in [[Outward Bound|outward bound]] activities. Before the war he was involved in [[Scouting]] and the setting up of a Juvenile delinquent/criminal rehabilitation centre based on outbound activities.\n\nHe served during the [[First World War]] and despite a leg injury, contrived to serve in WW2. He established and was part of a company which formed part of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary force]], evacuated from [[Dunkirk]] in May\u2013June 1940. It was realised soon after that in order to win the war Britain needed a larger quantity of capable officers, as the failure rate on officer selection was high around 65%, and a large invasion force was going to be required.\n\n[[Thomas Corbett, 2nd Baron Rowallan|Lord Rowallan]] was charged with setting something up based on the success of his rehabilitation courses. This resulted in the establishment of the [[Highland Fieldcraft Training Centre]] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20181104170018/http://www.hftca.org.uk/ HFTC]), at Feshie Bridge, [[Cairngorms]], in the [[Highlands and Islands|Highland and Island]] area of [[Scotland]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Rowallan : the autobiography of Lord Rowallan.|last=1895-|first=Rowallan, Thomas Godfrey Polson Corbett, Baron|date=1976|publisher=P. Harris|isbn=0904505111|location=Edinburgh|oclc=3650193}}</ref>\n\nPost war in 1977 the [[British Army|Army's]] [[Regular Commissions Board]] was again suffering a high failure rate (70%+) at Officer Selection and Training, and during research rediscovered the HFTC success and established a Rowallan Company at [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|RMA Sandhurst]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sandhurst : a tradition of leadership|others=Kent-Payne, Vaughan, 1958-, Pugsley, Christopher,, Holdsworth, Angela|isbn=9781781258231|edition= Second|location=London|oclc=1063725066|date = 2017-08-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1970s the [[Royal Navy]]\u00a0 and the [[Royal Marines]] found themselves in a similar but slightly different position to the [[British Army|Army]]. While applications for commissioned entry were reasonably stable many of the young men who appeared before the [[Admiralty Interview Board]]\u00a0 were judged to lack either the self confidence or the maturity to undergo training immediately after [[Admiralty Interview Board|AIB]] at either the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Britannia Royal Navy College, Dartmouth]] or at the [[Commando Training Centre Royal Marines|Commando Training Centre Royal Marines, Lympstone]]\n\nThe [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|RMA Sandhurst]] Rowallan course was adapted as a model for the [[Royal Navy|RN]]/[[Royal Marines|RM]]\u2019s Rowallan Division at [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|HMS Raleigh]] and was refined and shaped to better meet the needs of the service and, for every individual who was selected for this intensive course of leadership training, confidence and team building. Only two [[Royal Marines]] cadets ever undertook Rowallan Division and so the course syllabus was primarily focused on preparing young Cadets for entry to [[Britannia Royal Naval College|BRNC, Dartmouth]]. The [[Commandant General Royal Marines]] accepted the [[Navy Board (1964-present)|Navy Board\u2019s]] invitation to establish and lead the [[Royal Navy|RN]]\u2019s Rowallan Division\u00a0 and committed over 50% of the staff to command and run this course of training given the [[Royal Marines|RM]]\u2019s particular expertise and experience in command and leadership training.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Special Trust and Confidence The Making of an Officer|last=Cathy.|first=Downes|date=2013|publisher=Taylor and Francis|isbn=9780714633541|location=London|oclc=928016989}}</ref>\n\n== Directing staff ==\n'''Senior Staff List:'''\n\n* Major Rick Wiliams [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] WKhM [[Royal Marines|RM]] - ''Officer Commanding''\n* Lieutenant Commander [[John Lippiett]] [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] [[Royal Navy|RN]] - ''Training Officer''\n* Warrant Officer Class 2 David Langley [[Royal Marines|RM]] - ''Divisional Sergeant Major''\n* Chief Petty Officer David Attenborough - ''Stores & Support''\n* Petty Officer (PT) Michael \"Nick\" Carter - ''Instructor''\n* Sergeant Colin Grice - ''Instructor''\n* Sergeant Paul Pitcher - ''Instructor''\n\nOther members of staff included two [[Royal Marines]] who's duties included driving and who delivered overwatch safety protocols when activities were conducted in the field, \u00a0a [[Royal Navy]] [[chef]] to cook for staff in the field and a [[Women's Royal Naval Service|WRNS]] Leading Writer who assisted the Division's [[Sergeant major|Sergeant Major]] \u00a0with administration. An Instructor Officer was attached to the Division on an occasional basis to assist in the supervision of academic studies.\n\nThe emblem of Rowallan Division was the head of a [[Deer|highland stag]].\n\n== Course structure ==\nStudents on the course were given the nominal [[Military rank|rank]] of Cadet and were paid the equivalent of a new entry junior sailor.\n\nThe course schedule was not given to Cadets who were effectively at 30 minutes notice to move at all times. Generally the Division spent alternating weeks either in the field or in [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|HMS Raleigh]].\n\nWhen at [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|Raleigh]] there was generally 2 or 3 sessions of [[Physical education|Physical Training]] per day along with Practical Leadership Tasks. Emphasis during training was also given to improving Cadets\u2019 written and verbal communication skills with the purpose of improving their self confidence when addressing or briefing others. When it was necessary, individual/one on one Lecturing skills training was carried out that proved to be highly successful. Training activities in the field were conducted such as [[Map|map reading]], [[navigation]], [[first aid]], basic [[Radiotelephony procedure|RT]] procedures and [[survival skills]]. The [[Physical education|Physical Training]] included gymnasium work, [[obstacle course]]s and speed marches (often with loaded [[Backpack|Bergens]]) to improve Cadets\u2019 levels of physical fitness. \u2018Log runs\u2019 were conducted where teams of Cadets raced each other while each team carried a [[Utility pole|telegraph pole]] sized log - these were frequent events that all formed part of Rowallan's [[team building]] ethos.\n\nThe Division conducted many exercises in the field and used [[Dartmoor]], [[Bodmin Moor]], [[Snowdonia]] and the [[Brecon Beacons]] (including the [[Pen y Fan]] horseshoe). These exercises progressed though increasing levels of physical and mental duress while requiring Cadets to be individually selected at random intervals to plan, manage and organise a particular task that required innovation, imagination, demonstration of a command ability and good communication skills with the team. Cadets became very adept to \u2018expect the unexpected\u2019 that, with the background of their leadership training, assisted them in being able to think and act decisively when under duress.\u00a0 Where environmental conditions required it as a matter of safety, cadets were issued with the then in service [[Clansman (military radio)|Clansman]] combat net radio system. In early exercises Cadets slept in tents and ate standard 24 hour [[Field ration|ration packs]]. In later exercises cadets had to make [[Bivouac shelter|improvised shelters]] and were supplied with live rations in the form of hens and rabbits which had to be killed humanely under instruction and prepared by hand. Frequently crash moves of camps where trainees where ordered to immediately relocate would be initiated by the directing staff usually in the dark of night.\n\nTowards the end of the course, greater emphasis was given to the preparation and delivery of more classroom orientated activities such as short briefs, [[Lecture|lecturing]] and improving written communication skills and attending informal lectures from external speakers who had a record of excellence of [[leadership]] or personal achievement in their own areas of personal endeavour.\n\n== List of courses ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Course Number\n!Cadets Commencing\n!Cadets Completing\n!Success Rate\n!Notes\n|-\n|1\n|12\n|10\n|83%\n|<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n|2\n|24\n|14\n|58%\n|\n|-\n|3\n|18\n|16\n|88%\n|<sup>2</sup>\n|}\n'''Notes:'''\n\n<sup>1</sup>  Course uniquely included two Royal Marines Cadets who both successfully completed Rowallan Division and went on to [[Commando Training Centre Royal Marines|CTCRM Lympstone]].\n\n<sup>2</sup>  Course included Cadet Gary Pettitt who went on to attain the rank of [[Captain (Royal Navy)|Captain]] in the Royal Navy and Cadet Pete Williams who became a [[Commander]].\n\n== Course closure ==\nThe course was disbanded in 1981 due to [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|MOD]] cost savings measures but, in the short time that it existed, Rowallan Division had served its purpose well in [[Graduation|graduating]] significantly more young men into [[Britannia Royal Naval College|BRNC]] than would otherwise have been the case\n\nA reunion was held in 2015 in the form of a [[Mess|Mess Dinner]] at [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|HMS Raleigh]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Naval education and training in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rowallan_Division"}
